q3: No problems.  Depending on the purpose of the study, it might be helpful to know what it means to state an "objective" of a "game" when the game has real-world implications that don't appear to relate to that objective.  I could have been persuaded to play the game according to the rules if it appeared that something of even slight importance depended on my doing so -- even the "fun" of a "game."  But as it stood, I didn't see it as unethical in any way to break the "rules" of the game in order to increase the likelihood of a payoff for individuals, most of whom I assume have significantly less money than either I or the experimenters do.
